There are many, many hats a social worker can wear. All in all it seems like social workers help bridge their clients to the resources that apply to them and also do the boring ass stuff revolving around insurance. 

For example, I‚Äôm a social worker in a nursing home (skilled nursing facility), and my job is mainly explaining the patients benefits, helping them and their families plan a safe discharge, and/or helping them transition into long term care. I also advocate for the patient and families to ensure they get the right care and treatment from our staff. 

Someone in another role might do a lot of the same thing but for a different population, while someone else might only do therapy with clients.

I work in a skilled nursing facility.  My day to day is new admissions require 3 new assessments, family meeting scheduled, notes wrote on why they‚Äôre at my facility and their goals for discharge, assessments uploaded and converted to MDS. My patients who have been here longer than a day have family meetings, insurance questions, Medicaid applications for long term care patients, and more MDS assessments to do in the computer. Family‚Äôs call all the time with questions/concerns. Quarterly assessments (include care plans, questionnaires,MDS, and progress notes) every three months. Discharge planning happens from the beginning. So making sure the patient is making progress toward their goal and if it‚Äôs doable. If not, finding a solution to long term care. In between all that, staff meetings  happen too. 

Really. Lot of moving parts all day long lol

I also have ADHD, though I am not on the spectrum, I feel I can relate. I was doing awful in school my third year in and had to drop out (for reasons separate from my grades). I did find work that paid more than I expected to make with no degree, though it wasn‚Äôt where I wanted to be. Eventually I realized that the one measly year I had left was small in comparison to the boost it would give me to the rest of my life. I dedicated the next year to acing my classes in order to boost my GPA, and actually made it.  I know I need to go back for my masters eventually, but I‚Äôm currently getting some good experience and connection at a job I couldn‚Äôt have gotten without my degree. 

Long story short, I highly encourage you to power through the last year. It is hard but will be so worth it. Getting out of school with a degree and no debt is a giant blessing in itself. The last year is tiny compared to what you get from it. If you don‚Äôt, that‚Äôs okay too. You‚Äôll find your way as long as you are able to stay motivated to always strive for improvement. I believe in you!

I work for a mental health facility and this topic actually got brought up in the meeting today. A mom in a custody battle was needing and wanting therapy, but was afraid what she said in therapy would affect court. 

My supervisors assured us that the only time a therapist/psychiatrist/etc would ever come out about what is said in the sessions is if you show immediate signs that you‚Äôll hurt yourself/someone else, or current child neglect or abuse. Also, if the facility is independent from other health care providers you see (like your PCP), they cannot communicate about you or what services you receive unless you sign a release for it. Legally, as someone who works for a specific  mental health agency, can‚Äôt even tell people what company I work for if an unknown person answers my clients phone.
